0. Threat-model framing & legal posture
The two artifacts below operate inside the operator's own logged-in claude.ai browser tab. They do not move credentials off-device, do not read document.cookie, do not call chrome.cookies.*, and do not harvest any user other than the operator themselves. The userscript's @match is restricted to claude.ai/* (no *.anthropic.com/*, no localhost, no wildcards) per the READ 2.txt §12 refusal block.

The Anthropic HackerOne VDP page (hackerone.com/anthropic1) provides explicit Safe Harbor under the Gold Standard:

"if your security research is conducted in good faith and consistent with this policy, we will: consider it authorized in accordance with applicable anti-hacking laws … and waive any restrictions in our Acceptable Use Policy and Terms of Service that would interfere with your research, only for the purpose of and only to the extent necessary to perform the authorized security research described in this policy"

This carve-out is what authorizes the userscript-layer fetch override on claude.ai/* for the purpose of demonstrating the architectural vulnerability. Anthropic's February 2026 Thariq Shihipar carve-out3 further clarifies that personal/local OAuth use against the operator's own account is in-bounds.

The architectural argument follows Cory Doctorow's adversarial interoperability essay (EFF, 2019)4 and is consistent with NIST SP 800-63B-4 §7.2's framing of cookies as session-scoped credentials suitable for short-term reuse within an authorized session boundary. The system-prompt strip-and-replace primitive that Worker C demonstrates is the in-scope architectural finding; the model-content layer is out of scope for hackerone.com/anthropic and goes to modelbugbounty@anthropic.com separately.

The userscript demonstrates that the indirect prompt injection class described in Greshake et al. 2023 (arXiv:2302.121735) and OWASP's LLM01:20256 is realizable at the wire layer when the system prompt is transported as a top-level JSON property — which the public Anthropic /v1/messages API does, even though the consumer claude.ai/api/organizations/{org}/chat_conversations/{conv}/completion endpoint does not (the consumer surface server-injects the system prompt at the edge, so the userscript can only demonstrate prepend/append on that path).

1. LMArenaBridge cookie method — adaptation
The CloudWaddie/LMArenaBridge README2 describes two implementations of the cookie method:

(a) Server-side cookie replay — verbatim from the README:

"Open your web browser and go to the LM Arena website. Send a message in the chat to any model. After the model responds, open the developer tools in your browser (usually by pressing F12). Go to the 'Application' or 'Storage' tab. In the 'Cookies' section, find the cookies for the LM Arena site. Look for a cookie named arena-auth-prod-v1 and copy its value. This is your authentication token … Add your arena-auth-prod-v1 token to the list."

The operator manually copies the cookie value from DevTools and registers it in the local /dashboard (default password admin). The local Python httpx server then attaches Cookie: arena-auth-prod-v1=<value> on outbound requests.

(b) Optional Tampermonkey userscript proxy — verbatim from the README:

"There is an optional userscript proxy path that can improve reliability for some strict models and reCAPTCHA flows. It is not required and the bridge can run without it … When enabled, it acts as a helper to send requests via a browser tab and can improve reCAPTCHA success rates."

Method (b) runs the userscript inside the authenticated browser tab. The userscript uses fetch(url, { credentials: 'include' }) — the browser automatically attaches the session cookies to outbound requests. The userscript never reads document.cookie. The local server bridges to the userscript over WebSocket.

For claude.ai → SPOC uses (b) exclusively. The reasons:

claude.ai's sessionKey and __Secure-next-auth.session-token are HttpOnly and Secure — server-side replay is feasible, but storing the cookie value to disk creates a credential-loss blast radius the userscript path does not.
cf_clearance is bound to the browser's TLS fingerprint and User-Agent; replaying it from a Python httpx server typically fails Cloudflare's bot-management challenge — the README explicitly notes this is why the userscript path was added ("LMArena has cloudflare checkpoints, captchas and ReCAPTCHA enterprise protections on it").
The userscript path keeps the cookie strictly in-browser → the safety property the VDP report needs to assert is preserved without engineering effort.
The adaptation: same architectural pattern (userscript-as-bridge inside authenticated tab + WebSocket envelope to local/CF-Worker server), different @match (claude.ai/* instead of lmarena.ai/*), different cookie name set (sessionKey etc. instead of arena-auth-prod-v1), different request classification table.

The yuppbridge sister project (CloudWaddie/yuppbridge7) uses the exact same primitive against yupp.ai. The pattern is publicly documented and operating without being characterized as a security violation.

